<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0818-A"><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>As an attorney, he &quot;worked for the voiceless, those who were unemployed, poor and marginalized,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;Hale was behind bars, and his group was falling apart.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>The security chief was a federal informant who secretly taped Hale soliciting the judge's murder.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>It ended in the conviction of Matthew Hale, a white supremacist who fixated on Lefkow for having thwarted the movement he called his &quot;church.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>He is scheduled to be sentenced next month.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Because of the notoriety of the Hale assassination plot, few seemed to believe the killings could be a coincidence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Authorities placed U.S. District Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow under around-the-clock guard after she returned home from work Monday and found the bodies of Michael F. Lefkow, 64, and Donna Humphrey, 89.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>She sends him famous quotations from George Washington and Abraham Lincoln.</line><line>&quot;They asked if I recognized any of those two composites.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Police say extremist groups are just one of several avenues being looked at by authorities, though speculation among judges and lawyers about the killings has focused on Hale's group, which has a history of violence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Last year U.S. District Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow spent weeks under federal protection after a white supremacist in her court threatened to have her killed.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="10" sums="11,14,19,23,32,37,41,44,48,49"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="30" label="Lefkow's security detail was dropped" weight="1"/><scu uid="42" label="Hale was a previous litigant in Lefkow's court" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>He became widely known in 1999 when a supporter named Benjamin Smith went on a racially motivated shooting spree in Illinois and Indiana, killing two people, including former Northwestern University basketball coach Ricky Byrdsong, and wounding nine others.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Hale, the intense son of an East Peoria, Ill., police officer, was chosen in 1996 &quot;Pontifex Maximus&quot; of the racially obsessed &quot;religion&quot; -- replete with a &quot;White Man's Bible&quot; and Aryan marriage and communion ceremonies.</line><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Protected by federal marshals and hidden with her four daughters at an undisclosed location, Lefkow vowed Wednesday to return to the bench.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Monday night Lefkow returned from work to discover the bodies of her husband and her elderly mother in the basement of her home on Chicago's north side.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>It's amazing.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Police also are searching for two men whom they have described as &quot;material witnesses&quot; -- spotted near the Lefkow home hours before the bodies were found Monday evening.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;He doesn't really talk about his case -- I told him you have to stop, woulda coulda shoulda, it's over,&quot; Robertazzo, 53, said in an interview.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;This horrible tragedy has got to serve as the basis for a substantial increase in security for judges and their families,&quot; U.S. District Judge Wayne R. Andersen said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>While the case was working its way through the courts, prosecutors said later, Hale -- who called Lefkow &quot;corrupt&quot; and a &quot;probable Jew&quot; -- asked his security chief for Lefkow's home address and tried to persuade him to assassinate her.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Authorities would only say that they are casting a &quot;wide net&quot; for information from anyone connected with Hale, stopping well short of describing him or any of his supporters as suspects in the case.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Laura Lefkow, the 20-year-old daughter of Joan and Michael Lefkow, said in an e-mail to the AP on Wednesday that her father was a true gentleman.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Mourners filed slowly past the casket of attorney Michael Lefkow, his trademark gray fedora resting on top.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Both are white.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Matt's venom right now is with the FBI.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>A federal jury last year found Hale, 33, guilty of trying to arrange Lefkow's murder.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>A relatively mild one called her a &quot;sycophantic cow&quot; who did the &quot;Jews' bidding.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>Lefkow, 61, spoke publicly Wednesday for the first time since the slayings, telling The Sun-Times that she is &quot;just furious&quot; that the killings might be linked to her job.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>While the Chicago police said they were investigating 271 tips that poured into a hot line by 5 p.m. Friday -- including 141 that followed the release of composite sketches of two white men seen near the judge's home -- Hale and his sympathizers clearly remain a focus of the investigation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>U.S. District Judge Marvin E. Aspen also called for more protection.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;We have safe communities, they move in, and they bring the crime with them.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>According to a report in Wednesday's issue of The Chicago Sun-Times, the authorities are also pursuing telephone calls made to Lefkow's home Sunday night from a correctional facility.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>The phrase is the standard response that white supremacists encourage their supporters to give to government interrogators.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>A Justice Department official in Washington confirmed Tuesday that FBI agents were &quot;looking at any possible connection related to any case that the judge has handled.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Hate-group experts who have tracked Hale's &quot;Creativity&quot; movement for a decade say that the growth of his World Church of the Creator was a textbook example of a magnetic, racially obsessed activist who surrounded himself with adoring followers and used controversy to gain notoriety in extremist circles.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Both had been shot.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>His communication to the outside world was curtailed and his extremist followers left in disarray.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>A security detail of federal marshals was guarding Lefkow and other family members at an undisclosed location.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>The shootings came a month before white supremacist Matthew Hale was to be sentenced by another judge for soliciting an undercover FBI informant to murder Lefkow, who had ordered Hale to change the name of his extremist group as part of a trademark lawsuit.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="25" label="Matthew Hale is a white supremacist" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="42" label="Hale was a previous litigant in Lefkow's court" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Though she has been described by those who monitor hate groups as Hale's &quot;middle-aged mistress,&quot; Robertazzo said their relationship was platonic.&quot;It was suggested by Matt,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>A task force of federal agents and Chicago police detectives fanned out Tuesday through a residential neighborhood, searching for clues in the shooting deaths of the husband and mother of a federal judge who had been targeted for murder by a white supremacist group.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="25,51"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="7" label="Lefkow's mother and husband died of gunshots" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>He considered it a targeted attack.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo's comments, and the material she gave the authorities, provide the fullest picture yet of the prison life of Hale, who first encountered Lefkow when she presided over a trademark-infringement lawsuit in which an Oregon group tried to block him from using the World Church name.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>On average, about 700 threats are made against court officers each year, according to the Marshals Service, which secures federal courthouses across the country.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Confined to his cell 23 hours a day, Matthew Hale sings opera loud enough for neighboring inmates to join in.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Careful not to push the evidence too far too fast, a police supervisor said Tuesday that investigators are looking in &quot;many, many directions.&quot;</line><line>At 4 p.m., one of the Lefkows' four daughters hurriedly entered the house to grab a gym bag, but did not see her father or grandmother before she left for a workout.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>(End optional trim)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Turner said he told the agents only: &quot;I have nothing to say.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Beckham reported from Chicago and Braun from Washington.</line><line>A U.S. marshal's official said Tuesday that the cameras were removed after only a few weeks -- with the judge's approval.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>She said they stayed until 5:30 a.m. Thursday, mainly working on the computer, but also quizzing her about her whereabouts Monday, when Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow of U.S. District Court returned to her Chicago home to find the bodies of her husband and mother.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="3" sums="12,14,42"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/><scu uid="6" label="Murders occured on February 28" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;We both like classical music,&quot; she added.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>The authorities would not say where or when the two men, one in his mid-20s and the other aged 50 to 60, were seen or whether they were suspects or witnesses.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>A security detail that had patrolled nearby pulled out.</line><line>Days after Hale was notified that he had failed the Illinois state bar exam in 1999, Benjamin Smith -- a Hale disciple -- went on a shooting rampage through Chicago's north shore, aiming at minorities with a.22-caliber pistol.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>The only gifts he is allowed, Robertazzo said, are paperback books.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>He vowed to &quot;teach this judge a lesson.&quot;</line><line>Hale is virtually isolated from the outside world, not allowed contact with other prisoners and barred from any visitors except for his family.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>It wouldn't be legal in my opinion, but it wouldn't be wrong.&quot;</line><line>Bearing down with grand jury subpoenas and teams of interrogators, federal agents and Chicago police sought two men for questioning Thursday in connection with the execution slayings of a federal judge's husband and mother, pressing for information from followers of a white supremacist who insisted from jail that he had no involvement in the murders.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="4" sums="23,25,5,51"><scu uid="18" label="Investigators seek two men seen near home" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="35" label="Hale denies involvement in the murders" weight="2"/><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>Several telephone calls to Robertazzo's home went unanswered, but Hutcheson said Robertazzo told her agents &quot;wanted to know why Kathy and I talk so much.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>But after the judge ordered World Church of the Creator to change its name and imposed $200,000 in sanctions, Hale approached one of his aides and urged the judge's murder.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>&quot;The Internet is plastered with information about every one of us.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo said that her own racial views were rooted in her rape, at 13, by a black man.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>But several law-enforcement officials and media reports Wednesday indicated that task force members were leaning toward considering it a premeditated crime.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>A friend of Hale's, Kathleen Robertazzo, told The New York Times and Chicago Tribune in Saturday's editions that authorities seized 100 letters Hale sent her from prison and made copies of her computer hard drive.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>&quot;They're clearly heading down the hate group angle.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>But judges get no special protection once they leave the courthouse unless a specific threat arises.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>She added, &quot;It's obvious they're trying to link Matt to the killings.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Times researcher Lianne Hart in Houston contributed to this report.</line><line>Law enforcement clearly has a lot to look at there,&quot; said Devin Burghart, who monitors white supremacist groups for the Center for New Community, a Chicago-based activist organization.</line><line>Jim Molloy, Chicago's chief of detectives, said the slayings occurred between 10:30 a.m. and 4 p.m.</line><line>He ran twice for county judge, but was unsuccessful.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>He is scheduled to be sentenced in April.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>(Begin optional trim)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>These and other tidbits about Hale, the Aryan leader convicted last year of plotting to kill a federal judge whose mother and husband were slain this week, are in the cache of letters federal agents seized here on Thursday from the home of Kathleen Robertazzo, his frequent correspondent.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="25" label="Matthew Hale is a white supremacist" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="32" label="Investigators seized communication records" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;They've taken him out of his cell where he is working his case.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>The judge and her husband briefly received protection last year during the trial of a white supremacist who later was convicted of trying to arrange her murder.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>There are many marshals and other law officers in federal courthouses to provide protection for judges and others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>She said that, despite his atheism, Hale at one point &quot;prayed to God he wanted to die,&quot; and &quot;felt this warm wave of peace go through his body.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>She noted that Hale had said he wanted to &quot;exterminate&quot; her, but said his &quot;is a one-sided war in which this court is not embroiled.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Since his arrest in January 2003, Hale has been held at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Chicago under special administrative measures that severely restrict his communication with the outside world.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;Both of them were on crutches.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>After interviewing her for about 90 minutes on Tuesday, Robertazzo said, federal agents returned to her home in this northwest suburb of Chicago the next night at 8 with state and local police officers -- and a subpoena.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>They didn't have a chance.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, Chicago Police Superintendent Phil Cline and a number of federal judges were present.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;He came back from the dead with those three little revelations.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Chief of Detectives James Molloy described the two men in the sketches as &quot;persons of interest&quot; whom police want to interview based on witness statements from the neighborhood.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Hale's conviction in April 2004 brought a sense of relief to the judge and her family.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He invited her to meet him at O'Hare International Airport during a four-hour layover the next year, and she took him to speak at the public library here in 2001.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>The couple often held hands.</line><line>He has denied any involvement in the slayings, which he called &quot;a heinous crime.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Afterward, the Lefkows found their life easing again.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>&quot;Nobody is going to intimidate me off my duty,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>&quot;It was just cold-blooded.</line><line>A federal source who spoke to the AP on condition of anonymity said a shard of broken glass from a broken window in the Lefkow home contained a fingerprint and was flown to Washington for examination.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>&quot;They asked if there was an encrypted code, a cryptic message or an encoded thing.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>In an interview with the Chicago Sun-Times, Judge Lefkow said she could not say whether the murders of her husband and mother &quot;has anything to do with Matt Hale or any of his followers, but I do believe it was a hit -- not a random thing.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Lefkow, 61, had been singled out by Hale and his followers after she presided over a civil case in which his group -- World Church of the Creator -- was sued by a similarly named group for copyright infringement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>The FBI offered a reward on Friday of up to $50,000 for information in the case, which is to be profiled Saturday on the &quot;America's Most Wanted&quot; television show and has been part of President Bush's morning briefing each day this week.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Hale was convicted last April of soliciting his group's &quot;security chief&quot; to kill Judge Lefkow after she enforced a federal appeals court ruling that forced the &quot;creativity&quot; church to change its name.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The judge at first ruled in Hale's favor.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Two U.S. district judges who work with Lefkow called for officials Wednesday to reassess security arrangements for the nation's federal judiciary.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>But, she added, &quot;I don't hate all black people, I don't hate all Jews,&quot; and she said that &quot;white supremacy is a misnomer.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Hale's followers did not comply, and Lefkow responded by threatening to fine the organization $1,000 a day.</line><line>The group also made inroads with neo-Nazi factions in state prisons by distributing white supremacist tracts under the guise of spiritual materials, Burghart said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>&quot;This is a hit,&quot; McDonough said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo, a freelance court reporter, said she first contacted Hale, the self-described Pontifex Maximus of the World Church of the Creator, by e-mail in 1999, amid public debate over the Illinois bar's decision to reject him even though he had passed the bar exam.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>More than once since then, someone posted the judge's address on the Web and pasted in a biography and photograph of her husband Michael Lefkow, a 64-year-old lawyer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;When you go after a federal judge, you're just asking for trouble,&quot; Burghart said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;I totally condemn it, and I want the perpetrator caught and prosecuted.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>There's a clear history there.</line><line>The victims apparently were killed in the basement, where investigators reportedly recovered two.22-caliber shell casings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>According to Adam Schupak, associate director of the Anti-Defamation League of the B'nai B'rith in Chicago, Turner suggested in an April 2003 broadcast that Judge Lefkow was &quot;worthy of being killed.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>&quot;The crime has to be aimed at affecting a judge's official duties,&quot; said Scott Mendeloff, who helped lead a team of federal prosecutors in the conviction of Timothy J. McVeigh for the 1995 Oklahoma City federal building bombing.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;We're going to be vague and general for the time being,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>A worker in a nearby church reportedly noticed the two men sitting in a red Ford Escort idled in a no-parking zone near the Lefkow home, several hours before the bodies were discovered.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>But her ruling was overturned on appeal, and she later held him in contempt.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>It's not fair to go after my family.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;I told him, `Only if I can wear a T-shirt that said: Not Lefkow,' &quot; Bradley recalled.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>White supremacists viewed Hale as a political prisoner and raised money for his defense.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Lefkow ruled in Hale's favor and dismissed the case.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Investigators said they were not ruling out any possibilities, but were taking a hard look at any involvement by domestic extremist groups.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Lefkow sided with Hale, but an appeals court overruled her.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="42" label="Hale was a previous litigant in Lefkow's court" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Hutcheson said Hale told her that the day after the murder he was abruptly moved to a new cell &quot;that didn't have anything in it.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>In 2003, marshals managed special security for 20 federal judges and prosecutors.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Authorities have pressed his supporters about their communications with the jailed extremist and the possibility of involvement by leaderless &quot;lone wolf&quot; killers.</line><line>FBI and Chicago law enforcement officials have declined to speak publicly about any theories.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>FBI officials have said they do not have a suspect.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>The evidence is still being worked up,&quot; said James Molloy, chief of detectives.</line><line>Besides, she wrote, she had not seen or heard of &quot;any suspicious conduct by any member of World Church in or around her home, her office or places that her immediate family members frequent.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Investigators are hoping an abundance of physical evidence left behind in the basement where the killings of Lefkow's husband, Michael, and her 89-year-old mother, Donna Humphrey, occurred will point to specific suspects.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>FBI Agent Robert D. Grant said one avenue of investigation was white supremacist Matthew Hale and his associates.</line><line>Humphrey and Lefkow's 64-year-old husband had been shot multiple times, according to the Cook County Medical Examiner's office.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He is studying Latin and reading everything from the Federal Rules of Procedure to Agatha Christie.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>My sentencing date is April 6.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>But Burghart and others say that Hale's demonization of Lefkow was a perplexing act of self-destruction.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Several of the daughters cried, but Lefkow appeared to comfort some mourners.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Throughout the trial and after Hale's conviction, friends said, the Lefkows -- who had lived on the same quiet residential street for 20 years -- clung to familiar routines.</line><line>He killed two people and wounded nine.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>All the authorities will find on her hard drive, she added, was a &quot;rant and rave about he's being railroaded.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>Lefkow found her husband, Michael F. Lefkow, 64, and her mother, Donna Humphrey, 89, shot to death in their basement when she returned home from work on Monday.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="Evidence - shell casings" weight="3"/><scu uid="6" label="Murders occured on February 28" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Authorities would not say if they were witnesses or suspects, but the source said investigators have reviewed photo files of &quot;creativity&quot; supporters, looking for matches.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>At the federal courthouse, where Joan Lefkow had worked since her 2000 appointment to the bench by President Bill Clinton, disbelief defined the day.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo, a friend of five years who shares Hale's racial views, said that the authorities took 100 of his letters, written in pencil on yellow legal paper, and made copies of her computer hard drive, promising to search her e-mail for secret messages to supporters.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>U.S. District Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow told a newspaper Wednesday she fears the murders of her husband and mother may have been related to her job, saying she is furious over what she called a &quot;cold-blooded&quot; attack.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="9" sums="10,14,30,33,36,38,40,44,8"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>The aide was an FBI informant, and his conversations with Hale were secretly recorded.</line><line>But we haven't excluded any scenarios either.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;I told him it would be incest.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Authorities stressed that federal agents and local detectives had not yet narrowed the scope of their investigation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Staff writer Christopher Lee contributed to this report, as did special correspondent Kari Lydersen in Chicago, new researcher Madonna Lebling and research editor Lucy Shackelford.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;I only hope they seriously want to apprehend the animal instead of railroading the innocent,&quot; his statement continued.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;Obviously, Matt Hale and his prior conviction is an avenue we have to explore,&quot; FBI special agent Robert D. Grant said Friday as he announced a $50,000 reward for information in the case.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Lefkow received special protection for about two weeks after Hale's arrest in 2003, but it was then withdrawn with her concurrence, said Shannon Metzger, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Marshals' office.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>David Hale' told the authorities that he came home from his maintenance job at 1:30 p.m. Monday, took a nap, ate dinner and watched a movie with his children, then went to a local convenience store that has a security camera.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Lefkow initially had ruled that Hale could keep the name.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Hale is now being held in a federal prison under rules that severely restrict his contact with outsiders and is scheduled to be sentenced for the murder solicitation conviction April 6th.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>He is representing himself and is being held under special measures, reserved for terrorists, that restrict his contact with the outside world, allowing only his parents to visit him, each for an hour, every other week.</line><line>All of his books and papers have been taken away from him after this.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;She endured it with dignity,&quot; Pallmeyer said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>&quot;They're shaking the trees for anyone and anything they can possibly find,&quot; said a source familiar with the investigation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The freelance court reporter said that the agents had seized dozens of letters Hale sent to her from his tightly monitored cell in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in downtown Chicago.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo said agents also asked about her familiarity with the Lefkows' neighborhood and the color of her car.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Hale claimed 30,000 followers, although hate-group experts said those numbers were inflated.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Hale's backers railed against the judge and her family in Internet messages, even posting their photographs and address.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Both victims had been shot to death.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>The police refused to discuss whether these men might be connected to the hate groups that have been a prime focus of the investigation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;Through the entire Matthew Hale trial, we were concerned,&quot; said U.S. District Judge Wayne R. Andersen, who since the murders has urged the Justice Department to reassess the security arrangements it provides to judges and their families.</line><line>The war of words against U.S. District Judge Joan Lefkow lasted two years, a baffling, ominous campaign.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="12,23,32,42,44"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;I imagine my husband must have just walked into something,&quot; Lefkow said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Hale, 33, faces sentencing next month for soliciting an FBI informant to kill Lefkow after she ruled against him in a trademark lawsuit.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>The source said police also were analyzing a bloody footprint left at the home.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo said that Hale &quot;was starving&quot; when his breakfasts of two hard-boiled eggs and two boxes of cereal, and lunch of a tuna salad stuffed green pepper, was cut in half because of budget problems, and that he had been fighting the flu.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>More than two dozen police and federal marshals were outside the church, and the line to enter stretched down the block.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>An accomplished classical violinist and a graduate of Southern Illinois University law school, Hale revived the faction.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;Only an idiot would think I would do this.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Who would do this?</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>They remembered that he would sometimes show up at the federal courthouse to take his wife, U.S. District Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow, to lunch and brought her flowers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Investigators have questioned Hale about the war of nerves he once waged and about lingering resentment of Judge Lefkow.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>According to Hutcheson, agents sought Robertazzo's phone records, searched for firearms and seized the home computer she uses in her work as a freelance court reporter.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>At least three times, Potok said, the Lefkows' home address was posted on the Web.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>In the letters, she said, Hale describes singing opera in jail, taking Prozac and being buoyed by the presence of a man with the same name as Adolf Hitler's boyhood friend.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>So she has sent him philosophy by Nietzsche, &quot;The Time Machine&quot; by H.G. Wells, a history of Pearl Harbor, the Agatha Christie mysteries, anything in Latin and, most recently, the 1.7-pound Rules of Procedure.</line><line>&quot;We like to talk about history.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>Matthew Hale, the white supremacist convicted last year of plotting to kill a federal judge, sent a statement through his mother on Thursday condemning the murder of the judge's husband and mother as a &quot;heinous crime&quot; that he had nothing to do with.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="25" label="Matthew Hale is a white supremacist" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>At his law office one day, he asked attorney Paul Bradley if he could start locking a hallway door that had always been open to the public.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Federal agents seized telephone and computer records from one residence in the Chicago area and interrogated relatives and supporters of Matthew Hale, the leader of an extremist faction known as the World Church of the Creator.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/><scu uid="32" label="Investigators seized communication records" weight="1"/><scu uid="33" label="Investigators seized computer records" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Judge Lefkow was a late entrant in the saga of Hale and his World Church of the Creator -- the extremist group he founded to espouse a doctrine of &quot;racial holy war.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Held in virtual isolation in a federal detention facility while awaiting sentencing for a 2004 federal conviction for trying to arrange the murder of U.S. District Court Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow, Hale told his mother in a brief telephone call Thursday that none of his followers played any part in Monday's murders of Lefkow's relatives.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="2" sums="29,8"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="35" label="Hale denies involvement in the murders" weight="2"/><scu uid="40" label="Hale is in prison" weight="2"/><scu uid="6" label="Murders occured on February 28" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>Turner said Thursday that he had provided air time to Hale before his conviction last year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Meanwhile, investigators are hoping that an abundance of physical evidence left behind in the basement where the victims were killed will point to specific suspects.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;Matt thought, 'Oh my God, this is all these signs I'm supposed to keep going,&quot;' Robertazzo recalled of his letters.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Friends of the Lefkows said that the judge and her husband, a veteran labor lawyer, endured monitoring by security cameras and federal undercover teams during Hale's murder solicitation trial.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>It is red, like the Ford Escort said to have been spotted at the crime scene, but a Mitsubishi.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Judge Lefkow and the couple's children greeted people arriving at St. Luke's Episcopal Church for a 90-minute service that was conducted under tight security.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Lefkow and other members of her family have been in seclusion since the killings, guarded by a special protective detail of federal marshals.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The cameras were removed.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>The judge's husband had recently injured his leg and had surgery.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>The church worker told police that he told the men they were parked illegally and they drove off.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;There's simply no way that any supporter of mine would commit such a heinous crime,&quot; Hutcheson read from the statement, which she said Hale had written before calling his parents.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Lefkow refused to pass the trademark case to another judge, writing in 2003 that Hale should not be allowed &quot;to intimidate a judge off the case.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He slid into depression last fall, taking Prozac, but said he was buoyed when the adjacent cell was filled by a man with the same name as Hitler's boyhood friend.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Investigators believe the victims were forced to lie on the basement floor before being shot, the Chicago Tribune reported Wednesday, citing unnamed sources.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>&quot;However, we're actively pursuing that.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The collision course was set when Hale took over the reins of the World Church of the Creator, a supremacist sect started in 1971 by Ben Klassen.</line><line>When the Oregon church sued for copyright infringement, the case went before Lefkow.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Bayless and other officials would not provide specific details about evidence retrieved from the house, out of concern that leaks about the investigation might aid the killer or killers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line><line>Authorities also found a bloody shoe print and a blood-streaked mop, indicating there was an effort to clean up the crime scene, the Chicago Tribune reported.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>The judge was vilified on pro-white Web sites, and Hale was soon arrested for plotting her murder with an FBI informant who had infiltrated his group.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>&quot;They know where I was and I've been cleared,&quot; David Hale said Wednesday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>If the Chicago killings are eventually connected to Lefkow's work on the bench, it will be the first time that relatives of a federal judge have been murdered.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>&quot;If someone was angry at me, they should go after me.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;I don't want to live with blacks,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Officials said some evidence removed from the Lefkow home would be flown to the FBI's forensics laboratory in Quantico, Va., for analysis.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;You could tell they were relieved,&quot; a family friend said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;It's so unthinkable,&quot; the judge said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>He said police found much to study at the crime scene near Chicago's lakefront.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Turner said the agents, who work for the Joint Terrorism Task Force in New York, asked him if &quot;I had any idea who did this, why they might go after the judge's family.&quot;</line><line>Turner said Thursday he was not advocating Lefkow's murder.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>They still took evening strolls to stores and restaurants on Clark Street.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>But he cautioned that white supremacist &quot;lone wolves&quot; were capable of committing violence without direction.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>This is a group with a really remarkable record of criminal violence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Hale's group &quot;is pretty much splintered now,&quot; Burghart said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Lefkow had enraged Hale and his supporters when she ordered Hale's group to change its name after it lost a trademark-infringement suit to an Oregon church with a similar name, and later held Hale in contempt and fined him $200,000.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;He found a Chicago station that has classical music.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>Hutcheson, recalled the agents asking Tuesday at her home in East Peoria, Ill., &quot;Does he have a code, did he tell me something in code, which is about the dumbest thing I've ever heard.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Hale's dispute with Lefkow began with a civil lawsuit filed by an Oregon church with a similar name that feared people would link it to Hale's racist message.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Lefkow then was the enemy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo said that she happily provided the letters, since the government already makes photocopies of everything Hale sends, but that she hopes to get back the originals, which she kept in her office, ordered by date, secured by a rubber band.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>&quot;If I had the intent to do something bad, I wouldn't broadcast it,&quot; Turner said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>I told my mother not to answer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>U.S. District Judge Marvin E. Aspen also asked for a new look at security measures.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>If his people were going to target anybody, it would be his attorney.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Hale's father, retired East Peoria policeman Russell Hale, dismissed the notion that his son was involved in the slayings, saying he is under constant surveillance and the FBI closely monitors his phone calls and visits with family members.</line><line>The judge's remarks came as police released sketches of two men seen near the victims' home the day of the slayings, and as two of Lefkow's colleagues called for greater security for federal judges and their families.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="33,40"><scu uid="18" label="Investigators seek two men seen near home" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Under government-enforced restrictions designed to severely curtail his communication to the outside world, Hale is isolated from other inmates in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in downtown Chicago and can only speak to his parents by telephone briefly every two weeks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>The members of this group have been involved in murder, bank robbery, innumerable beatings and aggravated assaults.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Police said that deadly home invasions do not fit the community profile in Edgewater, a north-side Chicago neighborhood of stylish brick and wood-frame houses where the Lefkows lived for nearly 20 years.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;There is nothing spur-of-the moment or anything that would indicate this was a crime of passion,&quot; one official said, adding that the slayings bore the hallmarks of &quot;an execution.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>It's like they were worried I was going to get a weapon and come out shooting.&quot;</line><line>We never acted on it.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>He did what most of these extremist leaders do: stir up controversy and bring in people who were dependent on him,&quot; said Devin Burghart, a researcher with the Chicago-based Center for New Community who has monitored Hale and his faction for the last five years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Hale, 33, has emphatically denied any involvement in the killings, but the pressure on him has risen exponentially this week, as he faces an April 6 sentencing amid mounting sympathy for the judge he was convicted of conspiring to kill.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Several of Lefkow's fellow judges said they also were frightened.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;Judge Lefkow is old news.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>&quot;She is one of the loveliest, most principled human beings who has ever walked the face of this earth,&quot; said one friend, who described the Lefkows, married in 1975, as &quot;caring and compassionate people.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>But the statute can only be invoked if the killing was an attempt to impede or retaliate against the judge.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>I send him jokes to keep his spirits up, famous one-line pickups and stuff and just things to make him laugh.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>&quot;There's simply no way that any supporter of mine would commit such a heinous crime.</line><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>But if Hale and his coterie of extremists have become the most obvious targets for questioning in the federal manhunt,the origins of their enmity toward Lefkow remain inscrutable.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Police gave little background about the sketches they released of two white men -- one believed to be in his 50s and the other in his 20s -- who were wanted for questioning.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;We're not going to become myopic,&quot; he added.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>Evelyn Hutcheson and David Hale, the mother and brother of Matthew Hale, the man convicted last year of plotting the murder of the judge, Joan Humphrey Lefkow, said Wednesday that federal agents had asked them whether Hale might have communicated something from prison in code.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="5" sums="21,22,29,37,6"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Michael Lefkow, a veteran employment rights lawyer, wore his trademark fedora.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Three judges have been assassinated.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>But a federal appeals court reversed her, and in November 2002 she told Hale that she had no choice but to order him to stop using World Church of the Creator on his Web site and in all printed material.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>But in the days since the judge stumbled upon the carnage inside her north side Chicago home, discovering the bullet-riddled bodies of her husband, Michael Lefkow, 64, and her mother, Donna Humphrey, 89, Hale's racially obsessed &quot;Creativity&quot; movement again has drawn intense scrutiny.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/><scu uid="7" label="Lefkow's mother and husband died of gunshots" weight="3"/><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;Matt is a separationist, I'm a separationist,&quot; she explained.</line><line>&quot;This defies logic that he had any animosity towards Lefkow, she ruled in his favor -- it's the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals,&quot; Robertazzo said, adding that Hale's main complaint these days is about his former lawyer's decisions.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>&quot;They both handled it courageously,&quot; said Thomas F. Geraghty, an associate dean at Northwestern University Law School and a close acquaintance.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Membership in Hale's movement surged in the months afterward, to as many as 88 chapters across the United States.</line><line>And he pressed followers to obtain her address and other personal information -- including pictures of her husband and four daughters -- that ended up posted across several extremist Web sites.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Robertazzo said she &quot;has nothing to hide.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>But the judge never complained to colleagues.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>CHICAGO - The police released composite sketches Wednesday night of two white men they want to question in connection with this week's execution-style slayings of a federal judge's mother and husband, in an investigation that has also included interviews with relatives, friends and sympathizers of a white-supremacist imprisoned for soliciting the judge's assassination.<annotation scu-count="6" sum-count="3" sums="11,41,49"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="18" label="Investigators seek two men seen near home" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="39" label="Hale was convicted of soliciting Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/><scu uid="40" label="Hale is in prison" weight="2"/><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>But according to sources close to the probe and several people questioned by federal agents, investigators are concentrating on Hale's relatives and a hard-core group of supporters in Chicago and his base in East Peoria, Ill. as well as white supremacist sympathizers as far away as northern New Jersey.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>After two years of taunts -- with the judge's personal information and family photographs posted on racist Web sites -- Lefkow could finally breathe easy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Many of his supporters have been cut off from contact completely after sending letters with white-power symbols, or posting his replies on the Internet, so Robertazzo keeps her correspondence more personal than political.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;They said they're looking for any communications between me and any of the members to see if there were plans to do anything,&quot; Robertazzo said Friday.</line><line>Hale's security chief had been working with the FBI.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>White supremacist leader Matthew Hale, 33, was found guilty in April 2004 of soliciting someone to murder Judge Lefkow.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Chicago police also released a sketch of two men wanted for questioning in the crimes and sifted through photographs of Hale's followers in an attempt to identify the pair -- who reportedly were spotted in a car parked near the judge's home in the hours before the murders.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>She remembered her grandmother as a woman &quot;who could do the Sunday crossword puzzle in pen&quot; and hand-made quilts for each of her children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>&quot;The case is too new.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>I'm just furious.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Mark Potok, chief of the hate group monitoring project at the Southern Poverty Law Center, said he believed it was &quot;highly likely that a follower or sympathizer of Matt Hale is responsible.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Metzger said Wednesday that the office was studying Andersen's comments.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;On one level, he was pretty smart about it.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Now, Robertazzo sends him postcards with pictures of animals every other day, and they exchange one or two lengthy letters a week.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Michael Lefkow thanked the law officers and friends who had helped the Lefkows and said, &quot;We hope Mr. Hale will repent of his advocacy of evil.&quot;</line><line>In the upscale, tree-lined Edgewater neighborhood where Lefkow lives, Eddy McDonough said he had seen squad cars parked outside the judge's house in the past.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>The source said investigators were in the process of questioning Hale supporters who attended his two-week murder solicitation trial last year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Privately, Michael Lefkow worried.</line><line>In January 2003, Hale was arrested by FBI agents and charged with trying to arrange Lefkow's murder.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="12,42"><scu uid="23" label="Hale solicited Lefkow's murder" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>Hale's mother, Evelyn Hutcheson, said her son also told her, in their weekly 15-minute telephone call, that he was moved to a different cell after the slayings were discovered on Monday and that FBI agents had visited the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Chicago to question him and nearby prisoners.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He writes &quot;that the founding fathers would be disappointed in the country we're living in,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Hutcheson said Thursday that a team of federal agents who showed up at her home in East Peoria, Ill., asked her about recent conversations with Kathleen Robertazzo, a supporter of Hale's whose house in the north Chicago suburb of Hoffman Estates was searched by federal agents late Wednesday and early Thursday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>&quot;There's nothing pointing us in that direction,&quot; said David Bayless, spokesman for the Chicago Police Department.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>We all thought it was finally over and done with.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Slurs against Lefkow and her family were common.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The former Florida state legislator had forecast a &quot;racial holy war&quot; that would leave Aryans victorious over Jews, blacks and other inferior &quot;mud people.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>The other, a man in his 50s, was wearing dark coveralls and a dark knit cap.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;It's just so hard to understand,&quot; said Judge Rebecca Pallmeyer, a colleague of Lefkow on the federal bench in the Northern District of Illinois.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>&quot;One kept putting his hand on his gun; I felt like such a suspect,&quot; Robertazzo said of the agents.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Returning to her home on the city's north side Monday, Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow discovered the bodies of her husband, Michael Lefkow, 64, and mother, Donna Humphrey, 89.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="9" sums="13,22,29,30,32,37,43,57,6"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/><scu uid="6" label="Murders occured on February 28" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Now a task force of investigators is trying to learn whether Hale's intimidating words led to murder.</line><line>At dinner parties, the Lefkows made light of the surveillance cameras installed outside their home before sitting down and saying grace.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;There's real concern that there needs to be a dispassionate, comprehensive look at security arrangements in light of these homicides,&quot; Lehman said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Funeral services for Judge Lefkow's mother, 89-year-old Donna Humphrey, were expected to take place in Denver.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Sometimes, she said, she closes with a &quot;message to your enemies: hope your penal implants malfunction,&quot; but that typically gets cut out by censors.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>In 1999, Benjamin Smith, a &quot;Creativity&quot; adherent, went on a serial shooting spree on Chicago's north side, killing two people and wounding nine others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>They said they were going to leave no stone unturned.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>&quot;She and her family were singled out for demonization.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Chicago police spokesman David Bayless said FBI forensics experts at the bureau's laboratory in Quantico, Va., would analyze ballistics evidence retrieved from the home.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>In 2002, Lefkow had ordered him to pay $200,000 for violating an Oregon group's trademark on the name World Church of the Creator.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Robertazzo told the Times the idea that Hale would be involved &quot;defies logic.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Hale was isolated in jail, awaiting sentencing.</line><line>Hale replied: &quot;Well, whatever you wanna do, basically.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>I totally condemn it,&quot; Hale told his mother, Evelyn Hutcheson, in a 15-minute phone conversation that was monitored and taped by FBI agents.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>But when the suspect was behind bars, Lefkow felt safe enough to drop the security detail provided her by the U.S. Marshals Service.</line><line>Molloy said the killing took place sometime between 10:30 a.m., when Lefkow's mother, Donna Grace Humphrey, 89, took a call from one of her granddaughters, and about 5:30 p.m., when Lefkow returned home.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>Both victims had been shot multiple times, according to the Cook County Medical Examiner's office, and a source told the AP that police found two.22 caliber casings at the scene.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>&quot;I fear that to be true, and that's the great tragedy of it,&quot; Lefkow said, according to an article posted Wednesday evening on The Sun-Times Web site.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Investigators released composite sketches Wednesday night of two men seen near the Lefkow home the day of the killings.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="19,43,48"><scu uid="18" label="Investigators seek two men seen near home" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Soon after, she said he told her, he found the words &quot;I love Matt Hale&quot; etched in wood paneling at the prison, and someone named Kubizek (like Hitler's boyhood friend August Kubizek), moved into the next cell -- though the Metropolitan Correctional Center has no record of such a prisoner.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The war of nerves, it seemed, was over.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>&quot;He sounded sad, he's worried, frantic, scared -- so many things,&quot; Hutcheson said, adding that Hale has no television but was monitoring news of the killings through radio.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>They are family-oriented people, very religious people, but not in a judgmental way.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He tells me, 'Listen to it at 7:30, and I'll be listening.' &quot;</line><line>&quot;White supremacy sounds more ominous.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>Dan Lehman, a spokesman for the U.S. Northern District of Illinois, said that Andersen had talked to Chief Judge Charles P. Kocoras about his concerns and that some other judges working out of Chicago's downtown federal courthouse had expressed worries since the killings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>When Hale and his colleagues refused to stop using the name, she ordered them held in contempt.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>&quot;I think there is an increased need and awareness because there are people who are interested in attacking the very fabric of our democratic society,&quot; Aspen said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>A window shard, spent shell casings and a bloody mop emerged as key pieces of evidence Wednesday in the apparent execution-style murders of the husband and mother of a U.S. district court judge in Chicago.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="3" sums="10,36,5"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="Evidence - shell casings" weight="3"/><scu uid="15" label="Evidence - a bloody mop" weight="2"/><scu uid="10" label="Evidence - broken window glass" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>At the height of the Hale trial, the Lefkows cheerily ignored the cameras during dinner parties and refused to cut back on nightly strolls through the neighborhood, recalled Michael Miner, a senior editor with the Chicago Reader newspaper.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;It was a terribly unjust thing for a really wonderful family,&quot; said Pallmeyer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>But other judges in the courthouse have been coming and going without special security.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>Lefkow had an extra security detail during Hale's trial last year, but it was disbanded after a couple of weeks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050302.0305"><line>In addition, Hal Turner, a white-supremacist radio host in New Jersey who said in 2003 that it would be illegal but not wrong to kill Lefkow said Wednesday that federal agents had also questioned him about his whereabouts during the Monday killings.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>&quot;Most people living here don't feel threatened, since this wasn't aimed at them, but we're in shock.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>They have asked for the public's help and offered a $50,000 (euro38,124) reward to shake loose information.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Hale was not linked to those shootings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>In an interview Wednesday for the Chicago Tribune, Lefkow said she always knew her job put her at risk but never thought it would endanger her family.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050303.0210"><line>Hale, 33, faces up to 40 years in prison for two counts of obstruction of justice and one of soliciting his security chief to assassinate U.S. District Judge Joan Humphrey Lefkow.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>Chicago Police Chief of Detectives Jim Molloy said the killings apparently were committed sometime between 10:30 a.m. Monday, when Donna Humphrey spoke to a granddaughter by phone, and 5:30, when Judge Lefkow found Humphrey and Michael Lefkow lying dead in the basement.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>Talking to one aide of &quot;intimidation,&quot; Hale began planning demonstrations in front of Lefkow's home and at the federal courthouse in downtown Chicago.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,42"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Tuesday, as marshals were again providing Lefkow with around-the-clock protection, and dozens of detectives and FBI agents began searching for a motive and suspect in the murders, speculation centered on the followers of Matthew Hale, convicted last year of obstruction of justice and ordering Lefkow's killing.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="38" label="Investigation focused on Hale's supporters" weight="2"/><scu uid="41" label="Hale was convicted of obstruction of justice" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>&quot;They're looking for coded messages,&quot; said Kathleen Robertazzo, a Hale intimate who said she was questioned twice this week by FBI agents, who also copied her computer hard drive.</line><line>Now we don't know what to think.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>At least two.22-caliber shell casings reportedly were recovered from the Lefkow residence.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="14" label="Evidence - shell casings" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>The precautions taken by U.S. marshals to protect them were scaled back.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Miner recalled Michael Lefkow as an &quot;intense and idealistic&quot; attorney who branched out from a poverty law practice into employment cases and mediation in recent years.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>The extremist leader, Matthew Hale, is awaiting sentencing next month.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>Experts are analyzing several pieces of evidence, including a broken window with a fingerprint, a bloody footprint and cigarette butts.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>But when she was overruled by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, she ordered Hale's group to change the name it used on the books it sold at rallies and over the Internet.</line><line>&quot;We both laughed about it, but I could tell he was concerned.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>Supremacy means you want to rule over somebody.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>As a result, federal investigators are pursuing the notion that the judge's relatives could have been targeted by white supremacists acting without guidance.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>He loves the Roman Empire.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>&quot;This horrible tragedy has got to serve as the basis for a substantial increase in security for judges and their families,&quot; U.S. District Judge Wayne R. Andersen said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>In taped conversations, the informant asked the Pontifex Maximus if &quot;we're gonna exterminate the rat.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>Autopsies conducted Tuesday by Cook County medical examiners confirmed that the victims died from multiple gunshot wounds.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0139"><line>Hale, who called himself the Pontifex Maximus of his self-styled World Church of the Creator, said Smith was a martyr &quot;who gave his life for us.&quot; After Lefkow ordered the group to change its name, Hale said a &quot;state of war&quot; existed between the judge and the organization.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>&quot;If someone was angry at me, they should go after me.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>They think Matt's getting his message out in code.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>When she went to the bathroom and sat for a minute to collect her thoughts, Robertazzo said, an agent asked, &quot; 'How long are you going to be up there?'</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>According to testimony in Hale's murder solicitation trial, he told aides that Lefkow's order &quot;places our church in a state of war.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050301.0146"><line>The FBI was drawn into the case because killing relatives of a federal judge is classified as a federal crime, punishable either by the death penalty or life imprisonment.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>One, a man in his mid-20s, was seen in a car near the Lefkow home.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>The victims apparently were forced to lie down on the basement floor before they were shot in the head and chest.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050304.0177"><line>His only permitted visitors are his parents, who get an hour each, every other week.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>The family has been in protective custody since the judge discovered the bodies on Monday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050303.0129"><line>It's not fair to go after my family,&quot; she said in an interview posted on the Web site of the Chicago Sun-Times on Wednesday night.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050306.0099"><line>As scores of police officers stood guard, hundreds of mourners filled a church Saturday to bid farewell to a federal judge's slain husband, less than a week after the judge discovered his body in their home, along with that of her mother.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="4" label="Lefkow's husband and mother were murdered" weight="4"/><scu uid="5" label="Murders occured in their home" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050302.0121"><line>&quot;The Internet is plastered with information about every one of us, and I fear -- and my family certainly fears -- that these kinds of incidents are going to be repeated unless there is a very high priority on the safety of judges and their families.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050303.0142"><line>In Bergen, N.J., a team of government agents also visited Hal Turner, the host of a white supremacist radio program that airs on short-wave frequencies.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050304.0158"><line>In 2002, a conflict with an Oregon religious group also known as the World Church of the Creator threw Hale's organization into turmoil.</line></document></collection>